<TEXT>
the former mayor and two former council members of 
the city of sweetwater were sentenced to prison terms monday for 
using their public positions to extort money from a local 
businessman on a zoning matter 
us attorney dexter lehtinen alleged in january that five of 
seven members of the council in the small city in western dade 
county participated in the scheme 
former council member carmen menendez 51 was sentenced to 33 
months with two years of probation by us district judge edward b 
davis after her conviction on counts of conspiracy and extortion 
former mayor irain gonzalez 49 and former councilman antonio 
duran 49 each were sentenced to 27 months in prison to be 
followed by a twoyear probation after their conviction on a 
conspiracy count 
the three could have faced a maximum of 40 years in prison and a 
fine of 500000 
two council members hugo alvarez and lucio cobian entered 
guilty pleas earlier and were scheduled to be sentenced wednesday 
the sweetwater officials were suspended from office by gov bob 
martinez following their indictment on jan 25 
the three sentenced monday were convicted by a federal jury 
before judge davis on may 29 attorneys for all three defendants 
said they would appeal the convictions and sentences 
the indictment stemmed from a request made by maurice barakat in 
june 1989 asking the council to lift a landuse restriction 
barakat who owns the holiday plaza shopping center had sold part 
of the land which left him with less than the five acres necessary 
for commercial zoning 
barakat asked the city council to remove the restriction so he 
could sell the additional commercial units more easily the 
indictment said the defendants allegedly told barakat he would 
have to pay them 10000 in exchange for a favorable council vote 
on his request 
instead barakat went to the fbi 
the councilmen voted to continue delaying action on barakats 
request until he paid the money the indictment alleged barakat 
paid menendez 5000 with fbi agents watching but then was asked 
to pay 6000 more according to the indictment 
sweetwater known in the 1960s as a rural outpost in western 
dade county has recently become a haven for political exiles from 
central america 
</TEXT>
