<TEXT>
a union representing more than 80000 
supermarket workers in southern california called off a strike set 
for early today and dedicated the night to discussing a new offer 
from supermarkets 
bob bleiweiss a spokesman for the united food and commercial 
workers union said a council representing supermarkets made a 
contract offer and the rest of the night was to be spent discussing 
counterproposals 
the food employers council made the new offer earlier sunday to 
prevent a walkout by store workers 
bleiweiss said talks would continue with federal mediator frank 
allen present bleiweiss would not divulge specifics of the offer 
david willauer vice president of the council also refused to 
discuss details 
its a comprehensive proposal for a threeyear contract he 
said its a complete contract that includes wage and benefit 
proposals we think its a real legitimate offer of settlement 
the council represents more than 800 ralphs vons lucky stater 
brothers albertsons and alpha beta food stores from bakersfield 
to san diego 
the union which represents 73000 retail clerks and 7300 meat 
cutters authorized a strike for 1201 am today if a settlement 
wasnt reached by then negotiations began last month 
both sides reported no progress during talks saturay 
the clerks and meat cutters were demanding higher wages and 
better health benefits said ufcw local 770 president rick icaza 
the biggest ssue is over health benefits said icaza they 
say they must reduce costs and want to shift the expense to our 
members were resisting that 
wages for clerks currently range from 4 to 1305 an hour meat 
cutters make from 931 to 1433 an hour 
