<TEXT>
the nations toughest state abortion law 
will be tested in federal court this week in what could be the 
first step on the road to the us supreme court 
only guams abortion law is more restrictive than 
pennsylvanias which was scheduled to go before senior us 
district judge daniel h huyett iii today one of the two laws is 
expected to give the nations highest court an opportunity to 
reconsider the decision that legalized abortion roe vs wade 
the significance of it is the race to the supreme court 
said kathryn kolbert of the american civil liberties unions 
reproductive freedom project whichever one gets there first 
raises the question for the court to reevaluate roe 
in a hearing expected to last most of the week huyett will hear 
arguments on whether legislation passed in 1988 and 1989 illegally 
restricts the rights of pregnant women and their doctors to obtain 
or to perform abortions 
contested provisions include those that require married women to 
inform their husbands before they can obtain abortions and that 
generally ban abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy 
other sections are similar to some the us supreme court 
declared unconstitutional in a 1986 pennsylvania case those 
provisions 
obligate doctors to provide pregnant women with information 
regarding fetal development and their rights to obtain child 
support 
require a 24hour waiting period between a womans visit to a 
doctor and the performance of the abortion 
make information available to the public from reports required 
from places that perform abortions 
kolbert and other opponents say the law interferes with the 
ability of doctors to follow accepted treatment and counseling 
standards invites uneven law enforcement and the harassment of 
abortion clinics and staffers forces families to make decisions 
contrary to their moral judgments and imposes reproductive choices 
on women but not on men 
but robert r gentzel a spokesman for the state attorney 
generals office said the commonwealth believes that there are 
indeed appropriate public policy reasons for all of the 
provisions 
he also maintained that the restrictions are permissible under 
existing supreme court rulings 
the pennsylvania law has been temporarily blocked by federal 
court order as has the law in guam a us territory in the 
pacific 
in the spring the guam legislature banned all abortions except 
when a womans life is endangered and outlawed all abortion 
referrals 
the us supreme courts 1973 decision in roe vs wade outlawed 
state regulation of abortions unless the regulations were clearly 
to safeguard the womans health 
the pennsylvania law is being challenged by planned parenthood 
of southeastern pennsylvania womens suburban clinic womens 
health services inc reproductive health and counseling center 
allentown womens center and dr thomas allen of allentown on 
behalf of all pennsylvania physicians who perform or make referrals 
for abortions 
