<TEXT>
bertha the first hurricane of the 1990 atlantic 
season churned along the gulf stream well east of the carolinas 
today after regaining strength temporarily lost during the night 
born as a tropical depression off northeast florida bertha grew 
quickly saturday into a minimal hurricane with winds of 75 mph it 
dropped below the 74 mph hurricane threshold sunday night but 
regained hurricane status today after its winds intensified a bit 
at noon edt today bertha had top sustained winds near 75 mph 
and was centered near latitude 353 north longitude 674 west or 
675 miles southsouthwest of halifax nova scotia said forecasters 
at the national hurricane center near miami 
the storm was moving northeast near 13 mph and was expected to 
stay at the same strength course and speed through early tuesday 
said forecaster miles lawrence 
earlier bertha kicked up the surf along carolina beaches and 
sent gusts up to about 45 mph toward bermuda 
but forecasters said that because it was already edging 
northeastward toward the open atlantic when it was born it was 
never much of a threat 
its mainly a concern to marine interests at the present 
time forecaster hal gerrish said 
he said bertha could reach the canadian provinces of nova scotia 
and newfoundland by wednesday or thursday 
tropical storm arthur which peaked with 70 mph winds thursday 
but quickly lost strength over the central caribbean had 
dissipated by late saturday 
