the american civil liberties union today 
filed a lawsuit against two school districts that permit prayer at 
graduation exercises and other school functions 
the aclu making good on legal action it had threatened for 
several months named the alpine and granite districts and several 
administrators in the suit filed in us district court 
the action was certain to touch off a legal battle that some 
including gov norm bangerter have suggested should be fought with 
state funds to ensure prayers would have a place in public schools 
it is with reluctance that the aclu has sponsored the filing 
of these lawsuits given the shortage of funds available to the 
school districts for important programs and teachers salaries 
aclu executive director michele parishpixler said at a news 
conference 
all of our efforts to resolve these problems out of court have 
been rejected we feel we have no alternative 
the plaintiffs include students who have graduated or are 
currently students in the two districts and a counselor and teacher 
in the alpine district in utah county 
parishpixler said earlier today that prayer in utah schools 
forces minor children into religious practices 
she said that although taking such an issue to court is 
always a gamble she felt confident the aclus utah chapter 
would prevail 
the filings culminate a monthslong dispute over the practice of 
permitting prayer at graduation exercises and other school 
functions in utah where about 70 percent of its 17 million 
residents are members of the mormon church 
in the time since graduation exercises marked the school years 
end the dispute has come to involve the aclu school districts 
the republican governor and a top official of the church of jesus 
christ of latterday saints 
the debate began in 1989 when a student at the jordan school 
district complained that a mormonoriented prayer at graduation 
violated the students civil rights 
the jordan district later banned graduation prayer but the 
issue remained active through the 1990 school year 
even so a majority of utahns appear to favor prayer at some 
school functions according to a recent poll for the deseret news 
and ksltv 
the survey found that 72 percent of those questioned said they 
favored prayer at commencement ceremonies while 69 percent said 
prayers should be permitted in schools nineteen percent said 
prayer at graduation should be banned and 26 percent oppose school 
prayer 
of those who identified themselves as mormons 83 percent would 
accept prayer in the schools while protestants and catholics were 
split on the issue by political party 76 percent of the 
republicans favored school prayer as opposed to 58 percent of the 
democrats 
bangerter has said he would ask the legislature to appropriate 
money to help the districts battle the lawsuit although house 
speaker nolan karras rroy has said he would want to study the 
matter before committing state money to a costly and potentially 
fruitless proposition 
in a sunday editorial the churchowned deseret news supported 
bangerters intention saying that otherwise the school districts 
would be forced to bear the burden of costly litigation 
the newspaper also drew a distinction between school prayer and 
those at graduation exercises where most graduates and visitors 
are legal adults and where even those of faiths different from that 
of the person praying would hardly suffer psychological damage 
the salt lake tribune however opposes both school prayer and 
spending state money to defend it and planned an editorial for 
tuesdays editions said editorial writer diane cole 
