his end this way and so soon after the film was finished 
junkerman said 
the filmmaker spoke from yonaguni island where he flew from 
tokyo to join mourners at itokazus funeral monday 
itokazu fished from his dugoutlike 22foot skiff junkerman 
said on shore it was clear he was an 80yearold man but when 
he was out at sea it seemed he was 20 years younger the sea 
really was his element he loved it 
junkerman who made the film for a japanese production company 
said he didnt start out with the idea of mimicking the hemingway 
story but last year there were no marlin to be caught and the 
filming developed into something like the novel about an old 
fisherman who hadnt caught a fish in 84 days 
hemingways old man fishing alone in the gulf of mexico hooks 
a swordfish longer than his skiff he manages to subdue the huge 
fish and tie it to his boat but sharks tear it to pieces before he 
can get it to land 
itokazu often said its not very difficult to catch a marlin 
but the thing one has to do is take your time and catch the fish 
carefully junkerman recalled 
he very much respected the strength and danger of the 
marlin he said 
marlin fishing was good this year and itokazu was out looking 
for the large slender billfish when he died junkerman said 
</TEXT>
