<TEXT>
newmarketonfergus ireland ap the european communitys 
agriculture commissioner on monday proposed a 30 percent cut in 
farm subsidies over a 10year period in an effort to end a dispute 
that threatens global trade talks 
ray macsharry made the surprise proposal at a private meeting 
with the agriculture ministers of the united states japan canada 
and australia 
this is the first time the community has put a specific figure 
on the table said european commission spokesman john cooney 
the us delegation reacted coolly it said it would be 
inappropriate to negotiate a proposal outside ongoing talks 
involving the nations of gatt or the general agreement on tariffs 
and trade 
this is not a place to cut deals said kelly shipp a 
spokeswoman for us agriculture secretary clayton yeutter who 
attended the meeting with macsharry the delegations from japan 
canada and australia agreed with the united states she said all 
are members of gatt 
the united states and 14 other farm exporting countries want the 
12nation european community to end its export credits system and 
cut direct subsidies for farmers 
the dispute is threatening the successful conclusion of the gatt 
talks on global trade liberalization however the us and ec 
teams expressed confidence an overall gatt agreement would be 
reached in december 
the socalled quint meeting of the worlds most powerful 
agriculture ministers was called by macsharry and held at dromoland 
castle about five miles outside shannon in western ireland 
several hundred irish farmers who depend heavily on ec aid 
demonstrated outside the meeting no gatt sellout was their 
slogan 
the other agriculture ministers gathered in ireland were japans 
tomio yamamoto australias john kerins and canadas donald 
mazankowski 
the five senior agriculture officials were assessing 
developments since the group of seven summit in houston in 
midjuly when the industrial worlds leaders spurred efforts to 
cut farm supports 
macsharry proposed cutting all european farm support by 30 
percent between 1986 and 1996 
the offer includes cuts that already have been implemented 
cooney said he cited reductions of 10 percent in support for crops 
and a 15 percent cut in livestock support 
it certainly is a substantive one proposal it cant be 
considered flippant cooney said 
the proposal will be presented to the european commission in 
september the commission would have to approve it before it could 
be considered at gatt he said 
gatt negotiators are to meet again in geneva in late august 
they agreed at a meeting last week to compile lists and costs of 
their farm support by oct 1 
the developed worlds farm subsidies cost consumers and 
taxpayers 245 billion last year according to the parisbased 
organization for economic cooperation and development 
