governors in both parties have voiced opposition to the federal 
proposal arguing that limiting the deduction for state taxes to 
10000 would make it more difficult for states to raise their own 
taxes and put pressure on them to roll back income taxes they said 
it comes after states have spent a decade absorbing cuts in federal 
aid and after most states have had to raise their own taxes 
dukakis said bush who used his read my lips no new taxes 
slogan so effectively in the 1988 campaign has made the deficit 
worse by delaying action and now in breaking his pledge is 
hammering the states 
if mr bush no matter how devastating it might have been to 
his poll ratings had moved early as everybody knew had to be done 
i dont think wed be in the kind of mess were in now 
dukakis said 
the letter pushed by dukakis and schaefer went beyond a milder 
mention that republican gov terry branstad outgoing chairman of 
the governors organization and gardner made in a letter to bush 
before the meeting 
dukakis letter said the administrations plan amounts to a 
suggestion that our citizens should pay a federal penalty tax for 
living in a state that has taken responsibility for paying for 
its own services 
the deduction issue affects states unevenly falling heaviest on 
northeastern states with high income taxes and not affecting those 
that have no income tax 
the governors made only brief mention of their opposition when 
