a mild rainy summer has been ideal for marijuana 
cultivation in the midwest police say as they work to weed out an 
expected bumper crop 
it isnt just the weather thats boosting production steppedup 
federal efforts to stop drugs from being smuggled into the country 
have driven up the price of marijuana encouraging the growers to 
increase their efforts according to federal authorities and law 
enforcement officials in several states 
weve had all this rain good hot humid weather which 
marijuana thrives in and plenty of people interested in making a 
little money said sgt jim hinkle of the illinois state police 
hinkle coordinates operation cash crop an eradication program 
the state runs jointly with the us drug enforcement 
administration 
illinois indiana kansas minnesota missouri oklahoma texas 
and wisconsin are expected to have massive tracts of cultivated and 
wild marijuana by fall officials said california though wracked 
by drought also is likely to produce a bumper crop of marijuana 
officials said 
the us drug enforcement administration says usgrown 
marijuana is netting drug dealers hundreds of millions of dollars 
annually cultivated high quality marijuana like the potent 
sinsemilla variety sells for about 2500 a pound hinkle said 
one plant can provide a pound of the drug he said 
the street price of averagegrade marijuana is about 160 to 
240 per ounce this year across the country up from 120 to 180 
an ounce a year ago according to the dea 
authorities hope to get the jump on pot growers before the 
harvest season which lasts for three months beginning in september 
in northern california over the weekend about 200 federal and 
state agents descended on prime public land to hunt for pot in what 
was called the largest marijuana raid in the state 
an even bigger problem officials say is finding ditch 
weed the wild plant has little potency but is used to cheat 
buyers by mixing with higherquality strains 
ditch weed grows in abundance in many states much to the 
consternation of police because it is an offspring of seeds 
planted when marijuana was cultivated to make hemp rope in world 
war ii drug officials say 
it is after all a weed and it grows and grows and 
grows hinkle said 
nebraska in 1989 eradicated more than 73 million ditch weed 
plants and 6300 cultivated marijuana plants thats nearly twice 
the number of ditch weed plants plucked in indiana which ranks 
second to nebraska in wild weed destruction according to dea 
statistics 
jeff hanson spokesman for the nebraska state patrol said the 
state has been a magnet for people looking for free marijuana 
i think word kind of spread around that we have marijuana 
here hanson said in a telephone interview we get a lot of 
outofstate plates on these rural dirt roads and you dont have 
to be superintelligent to figure out these people arent out there 
just to enjoy the scenery 
police everywhere say pot farmers are hard to catch because the 
land where marijuana thrives often is isolated 
many states rely on informants and aerial surveillance to nab 
suspects and spot marijuana plots illinois offers 1000 to 
residents who call in with information leading to a substantive 
arrest 
critics say the use of informants smacks of spying on the 
neighbors but law enforcement officials contend the publics help 
in eradicating illegal drugs is vital 
its difficult to catch these guys and to prove a case 
especially a cultivation case hanson said we really do need 
the publics help 
