<TEXT>
the house acted monday to protect the grand 
canyon from any further damage from the hydroelectric functions of 
the nearby glen canyon dam 
a bill approved by voice vote directs the interior department to 
operate the dam on the colorado river in arizona in a such a way 
that natural cultural and recreational resources downstream in the 
grand canyon are protected or improved 
rep george miller dcalif sponsor of the bill said that for 
more than 25 years the dam has been diverting water through power 
turbines upstream of grand canyon at times of peak electricity 
demand 
this has caused fluctuations in water flow that has hurt 
wildlife in the canyon and frequently left rafters stranded on sand 
bars conservationists argued 
enviornmentalists filed lawsuits demanding that the interior 
department do an environmental impact statement analyzing dam 
operations in 1988 a sixyear study concluded that the dam was 
damaging the canyon environment and last july the interior 
department announced that it would prepare the environmental impact 
statement 
the current management of this dam is a national 
embarrassement miller said the primary purpose of this bill 
is to take immediate and lasting steps to protect the resources of 
the grand canyon 
millers bill requires the interior department to take interim 
steps pending completion of the impact statement to protect the 
environment and mitigate and damage that has already taken place 
it directs the department to take longterm steps for operation 
of the dam after the impact statement is completed 
the bill still must be approved by the senate 
</TEXT>
