<TEXT>
a congressional conference committee approved 
a bill monday that would ban the export of unprocessed logs from 
most stateowned lands in the western states 
northwest lawmakers drafted the measure this spring to offset a 
shrinking timber supply as logging is prohibited on more and more 
public lands in an attempt to protect wildlife that inhabit 
oldgrowth forests including the rare northern spotted owl 
the proposal now goes to the floors of the house and the senate 
where approval is expected 
under the bill export of raw logs could continue on onefourth 
of the stateowned lands in washington but would be banned on all 
state lands in oregon california idaho montana nevada wyoming 
utah colorado arizona and new mexico hawaii and alaska are not 
affected 
backers of the proposal say it will keep at home about 600 
million board feet of timber threequarters of it in washington an 
oregon annually shipped to more lucrative markets overseas 
in each of the last two years about 36 billion board feet of 
unprocessed timber the bulk of it from private land has been 
exported from washington and oregon about 80 percent of the total 
national exports 
about one in four trees cut in the pacific northwest is shipped 
to foreign countries primarily japan 
when we are experiencing a tight timber supply as we are now 
in the northwest it makes absolutely no sense to be shipping raw 
logs overseas sen bob packwood rore said 
packwood and several other northwest lawmakers also advocate a 
ban on the export of raw logs from private lands but the bush 
administration as well as the timber industry strongly opposes that 
idea 
the bill would make permanent the temporary ban on raw log 
exports from federal lands in the western united states it also 
would close loopholes in the federal ban that allow some timber 
companies to obtain federal logs from a third party for their 
domestic mills while shipping their own private logs overseas 
</TEXT>
