defense attorneys slipped out a back entrance of the courthouse 
without answering reporters questions 
the state contended that the childs death was a malicious 
culmination of weeks of coes bizzare abuse 
but the defense said in closing arguments that the fatal dunking 
was an isolated incident in toilet training and that coes intent 
wasnt malicious coes attorney robert norgard argued coe should 
be convicted of a lesser offense 
all he meant to do was dunk bradleys head in the water to use 
the association with water to teach the child not to soil his 
pants norgard said in the heat of the moment he thought of 
something that was frankly unusual but he did not intend to hurt 
that child 
prosecutor john aguero countered there is no rational 
explanation for an irrational act this was a senseless killing 
bradleys death came two months after he was ordered returned 
from foster care to his mother sheryl mcgee coe and stepfather 
thomas coe 
mrs coe 21 has testified that during those two months her 
husband often forced the child to pick up feces with his mouth and 
ground his fist and cayenne pepper into the boys genitals 
she admitted to sometimes aiding in abuse and beating the 
toddler with pillows just before he died she pleaded no contest to 
seconddegree murder and aggravated child abuse and is serving a 
30year term 
norgard suggested that the jury find coe guilty of manslaughter 
citing the actual wording of the law as culpable negligence 
rather than an intentional act and reckless disregard for human 
life 
were not here to ask you to find coe not guilty that man 
did cross the line norgard said but hold this man responsible 
for what he did and not for what he didnt do 
medical experts have testified for the prosecution that when 
bradley died his body was covered with more than 50 bruises some 
of them more than two weeks old 
norgard also did his best to discredit the allegations of the 
principal state witenss sheryl coe saying she was trying to 
distance herself from the crime to make life easier on herself in 
prison 
because of news reports about the case the trial was moved from 
polk county where the death occurred to fort myers 
outrage over the case also led to the states passage of the 
bradley mcgee act which allocated 79 million for more 
childprotection workers 
a former florida health and rehabilitative services caseworker 
was convicted last month of felony child abuse for negligence for 
failing to provide a judge with a psychological evaluation of the 
coes describing them as infantile explosive and unable to handle 
children 
three other state workers were cleared of charges filed in their 
handling of the case 
