<TEXT>
fourteen research monkeys suffered 
heatstroke and died after being left outside as temperatures soared 
into the 90s the us centers for disease control said monday 
the rhesus monkeys which had been taken from their cages for 
deworming and health screening were discovered on the floor of an 
outdoor housing building at the agencys breeding and holding 
complex in lawrenceville 
the monkeys died july 9 but monday was the first public 
announcement of the deaths by the cdc 
cdc officials said it was the biggest number of accidental 
primate deaths in the halfdecade history of the research agency 
the monkeys were among a colony of 100 raised for research in the 
cdcs breeding complex 
researchers said heat usually doesnt cause abnormal stress for 
rhesus monkeys which are commonly found in the subtropical regions 
of india and asia as well as in the frigid himalayas of nepal 
everyone concerned with it is very upset that it happened and 
we are taking steps to see that it doesnt happened again said 
bobby g brown chief of the cdcs animal resources branch 
brown said the monkeys among 33 which had been taken from one 
section of the rhesus compound had been anesthetized to allow six 
animal handlers to safely deworm them and test them for the simian 
aids virus and tuberculosis 
the other monkeys suffered no ill effects from the treatment 
the cdc is investigating the deaths 
