<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
july 2330 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
knightridder inc reported a 648 percent drop 
in secondquarter earnings while times mirror co said its 
aftertax profit tumbled 447 percent both said the big drops 
resulted from comparisons to yearearlier profits that were 
inflated by onetime gains from the sale of assets 
in other earnings reports tribune co said its net profit fell 
25 percent and washington post co said its earnings decreased 75 
percent 
all the companies said their operations were affected by the 
weakness in the advertising climate 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
times mirror said it earned 470 million in the apriljune 
quarter compared with 850 million in 1989 revenue rose 53 
percent to 9066 million from 8613 million 
the company said 17 percent of the yearearlier profit came from 
the sale of timberlands 
robert f erburu chairman and chief executive said weak 
economic conditions continued to adversely affect the companys 
newspaper and other advertisingdriven businesses 
for the first six months the company earned 930 million down 
395 percent from 1538 million a year earlier revenue rose 4 
percent to 178 billion from 171 billion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
tribune earned 581 million in the quarter compared with 753 
million a year ago revenue rose 2 percent to 6562 million from 
6431 million 
the company said its operating profit from newspaper publishing 
fell 33 percent mainly due to losses at the daily news in new 
york profit at the chicago tribune improved but results at its 
other papers were flat or lower because of softness in retail and 
classified advertising 
operating profit for the newsprint group fell 83 percent because 
of lower newsprint selling prices and the adverse impact of a 
stronger canadian dollar 
for the first six months tribune earned 896 million down 20 
percent from 1121 million in 1989 revenue rose 36 percent to 
124 billion from 12 billion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
knightridder earned 446 million in the quarter compared with 
1268 million a year earlier revenue rose 22 percent to 5917 
million from 5787 million 
the company noted that twothirds of the 1989 profit resulted 
from the sale of the star news in pasadena calif and television 
operations net income from continuing operations in the latest 
quarter was up 143 percent from a year ago it said 
knightridder said advertising revenue at its 31 newspapers was 
under pressure with retail and general advertising revenue 
marginally higher and classified ad revenue down slightly 
for the first six months knightridder earned 705 million 
down 52 percent from 1473 million a year earlier revenue rose 
27 percent to 115 billion from 112 billion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
washington post earned 559 million for the quarter compared 
with 605 million a year ago revenue edged up 1 percent to 3796 
million from 3745 million 
the company said revenue at its newspaper division dipped 2 
percent as ad volume fell 9 percent at the washington post revenue 
at newsweek was up 6 percent because the latest quarter had one 
more issue than the yearago period 
revenue was down 4 percent for the broadcast division and up 11 
percent in the cable division 
for the first six months washington post earned 950 million 
down 69 percent from 102 million in 1989 revenue edged up 05 
percent to 7205 million from 7163 million 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
reuters holdings plc said july 24 that its 
aftertax profit jumped 27 percent in the first half of the year 
helped by strong sales in all major markets particularly europe 
reuters said earnings for the januaryjune period were the 
equivalent of 188 million compared with 148 million in 1989 
revenue rose 26 percent to 12 billion from 954 million 
the company said sales strength was partly due to the relative 
weakness of the pound during the period which made british 
companies more competitive in selling products and services in 
other countries the pound has since rebounded 
reuters said that conditions in financial markets remain 
difficult and cancellations of reuter services which were already 
high have recently risen further 
the company did not report separately for the second quarter 
which is not required under british law 
</TEXT>
