the soviet union has a new law forbidding state 
censorship of the media but the main censorship agency wont be 
abolished its director said in an interview published july 26 
chief soviet censor vladimir boldyrev said the glavlit 
censorship agency will continue to check foreign publications and 
audio and visual materials mailed to the soviet union for calls to 
overthrow the government or to commit crimes and for pornography 
war propaganda and material promoting racial or ethnic superiority 
the press law debated for months before it was passed by the 
soviet legislature on june 12 takes effect aug 1 it also gives 
any soviet citizen the right to establish a media outlet 
the law forbids publication of state secrets but the penalties 
are to be imposed on whoever leaks them rather than on the 
journalist reporting them 
it also forbids slander and abuses of privacy 
scores of unofficial papers have appeared in the soviet union 
their publishers must scramble to reach agreements with staterun 
printing houses to supply paper 
