editors note an american reporter looking for inexpensive 
accommodations in japan checked into a zen buddhist temple with the 
understanding that he would partake of the rituals he learned what 
its like to get whacked by a monk on the other side of the globe 
a former heroin addict has spent months in a buddhist monastery in 
new yorks catskill mountains trying to kick his habit here are 
two stories 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the burly blackrobed zen buddhist monk 
casually showed the wooden staff he uses to beat people who slump 
or sleep during meditation 
only later after it was applied to me with extreme vigor did i 
realize he was asking if it was all right to use it to improve my 
meditating stance 
we were in the laymens zen hall of myoshinji temple i had 
asked a friend to help me find cheap accommodation in kyoto and 
1333 for a night at myoshinji seemed quite within reason 
the only catch is that the guest must try to transcend reason 
through zen and accept the discipline aimed at enlightenment 
the monk kodo yoshitomi his bald head gleaming under the 
ultraviolet lights in a large matcovered room explained the 
basics of zen meditation he demonstrated the crosslegged lotus 
position with deep breathing and eyes focused on a point a yard 
ahead he told of chanting sutras and trying not to think 
i said that not thinking is difficult he laughed and agreed 
this is very hard to explain to mr foreigner says yoshitomi 
who is in his late 20s 
he told me to sit on a round black pillow atop a 2footsquare 
cloth mat after 15 minutes a master monk and 12 mostly 
middleaged students including a woman came into the room and 
assumed the lotus position on other pillows 
most of the students wore western clothes but a few wore robes 
the woman wore a coarse blue robe one man was with his teenage 
son 
we were lined up in two facing rows with the elderly master 
kobun harada at the front of the room the monks sounded a bell 
and wooden clapper to signal the beginning of deep breathing then 
a triple bell to mark the start of meditation 
yoshitomi walked up and down the rows brandishing the staff he 
stopped in front of one student who had been slumping the student 
still sitting bowed and lifted his hands in a prayer gesture then 
leaned over with his left hand gripping his right shoulder 
tap tap whack whack the staff swung into the left upper back 
of the student who then put his right hand on his left shoulder 
tap tap whack whack 
the student and yoshitomi bowed to each other and the monk 
walked on down the row 
i tried breathing deeply five seconds in five seconds out 
focusing just ahead and trying to rid my mind of thoughts the 
primary thought was that my leg was falling asleep aching and 
becoming numb traffic noise made it hard to concentrate 
yoshitomis soft footsteps grew closer he stopped in front of 
me glasses off whispered student sukuki hiroshi sitting 
beside me yoshitomi pointed to my watch and i took that off too 
i bowed down and the monk put my hand on the proper shoulder a 
couple of taps and the wood sliced through the air onto my upper 
back with two tremendous whacks i winced yoshitomi hit the other 
side of my upper back twice then put the staff against my spine 
and pushed me against it to straighten me we bowed and he moved on 
after the initial sting wore off i felt refreshed the beatings 
had gotten the circulation going again and the idea of being 
beaten made me want to laugh i returned to trying to meditate with 
renewed enthusiasm 
i succeeded in not thinking for a few seconds at a time but 
then id think hey its working im not thinking and return 
to the eternal internal jabbering 
i thought about whether i would be beaten again what wed have 
for breakfast my wife and children sleep sex and how to say 
these things in japanese 
i thought about things i had read about zen including essays by 
american trappist monk thomas merton that sought to bring together 
buddhist and christian contemplation i felt inspired to learn more 
about zen whose emphasis on simplicity selfdiscipline and 
oneness with nature is crucial to understanding japan 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900730-0169 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
but mostly i pondered the discomfort of the lotus position 
one foot tingled then ached then grew so numb i couldnt move 
my toes i glanced down thought i saw it turning blue and 
wondered if enlightenment was worth losing a foot 
but every few minutes especially when yoshitomi crept by with 
the staff i made sure i was sitting upright 
finally the bell rang the wooden clapper sounded four times and 
everybody changed leg positions the feeling was just returning to 
my leg when we began another 20minute round during which a few 
other students were whacked 
the bell and clapper sounded again and everyone stood up and 
collected thin mattresses from a closet and spread them on the 
floor in the sleeping room 
we had a tea break at a table with western chairs the other 
students were interested in my impressions of japan and in the 
variety of ethnic groups in the united states 
hiroshi said he had been studying zen every weekend for a year 
at the laymens center which has about 1200 participants another 
man said he had been coming for 10 years no one indicated a desire 
to become a fulltime monk 
i slept well despite the traffic loud snoring from some 
students and the lack of a shower 
at 5 am we were awakened and carrying our pillows under 
folded arms we were led singlefile along a street into the temple 
compound and into the 660yearold wooden temple 
the dawn was bright the air fresh and the temple grounds quiet 
except for singing birds and the scrape of our templeissue sandals 
against gravel i inhaled the aroma of ancient pines and felt this 
was about as far east as one could get 
we sat on our pillows on a tatamimat platform and two monks 
sat by the altar under colored banners 
we meditated for 20 minutes during which most of us were 
whacked then began a series of chants most students had memorized 
them but some read from a pamphlet 
the syncopated lowpitched drone of the chants accompanied by 
a drum was compelling and hypnotic at the end they slowed down 
and ended in a falling sound 
after another 20minute meditation we walked briskly around the 
temples outer stone platform for about 10 minutes then into 
another building for a breakfast that defined austerity we kneeled 
on tatami mats around some low wooden benches where yoshitomi 
explained the ritual for eating 
we gave a chant of thanksgiving two other monks brought in a 
tub of rice gruel and ladled it into our bowls after each person 
bowed and scraped the palm in a brisk gesture 
each of us also had a little bowl of fried tofu with grated 
radish and a small dish of pickles we put a bitesized offering of 
gruel on the bench beyond the bowl then ate quickly shoving in 
the wet gruel with chopsticks 
yoshitomi told us to save the last yellow pickle which we used 
with tea to wash out the bowls we each put our single plum pit 
into a bucket held by the monks stacked the bowls and put them in 
another bucket then stacked the benches 
back at the laymens center we swept the tatami mats and 
scrubbed them with rags then we sat on the mat in the sleeping 
room for tea cookies and an informal meeting we introduced 
ourselves and asked questions of harada the master who seemed 
kindly and easygoing 
afterward hiroshi gave me a ride to the midpriced hotel where 
i would spend the next night wallowing in the putrefaction of 
relative luxury but that didnt bother me because i knew now that 
it was all an illusion 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900730-0170 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
heroin addict keith scofield had three 
choices go to jail go to colorado for drug treatment or check 
into a monastery 
he chose the latter dai bosatsu zendo a buddhist monastery 
sitting atop a mountain in the catskills about 80 miles northwest 
of new york city 
scofield is about a third of the way through a selfimposed 
twoyear sentence as a zen novice using 2500yearold meditation 
techniques to relieve his craving for drugs 
if i had gone back into drug treatment i would have wound up 
back in jail or dead says scofield 31 a heroin addict since 
he was 13 five previous drug programs had failed him 
the reason i got lost into drugs is that i didnt care he 
adds 
in colorado he would have spent two years in a boot campstyle 
program where i would have been thinking dont just shave my 
head and have me scrub floors with a toothbrush give me something 
new something to be excited about 
scofields foray into buddhism began a year ago when he was 
sitting in loudoun county jail in virginia he was jailed in june 
1989 after he was caught shoplifting a violation of his 1988 
probation for drug possession that drug arrest came after he 
overdosed on heroin 
in his cell scofield began reading zen manuals and meditating 
after five months he went before a judge who gave him two options 
five years in prison or two years at the colorado military camp 
scofield encouraged by the tranquillity he had found through 
buddhism suggested a monastery as a third alternative 
the judge agreed with the understanding that if scofield left 
the monastery before his two years ended or if he broke the monks 
rules he would be jailed for five years 
last december scofield was freed and exiled himself to the 
remote monastery which can be reached only by a 20mile trip up a 
winding narrow dirt road his case was assigned to a new york 
probation officer 
since then scofields days have begun at 5 am with a regimen 
of chanting meditation manual labor yoga and spartan vegetarian 
meals 
some people thought i somehow scammed my way out of a prison 
sentence scofield says but if i had chosen jail i could have 
just sat tight done my time and walked out 
he also could have been paroled in less than two years 
conventional drug treatment gave scofield the rational reasons 
to quit drugs but no emotional or spiritual ones he says a year 
was the longest he stayed off drugs after conventional treatment 
the introspective searching of zen philosophy fills that void 
he says 
drugs are a symptom youve got to come to a deeper 
realization of the truth says monastery vice abbot junpo dennis 
kelly 
kelly who was reluctant to let scofield come to the monastery 
now gives 2to1 odds that buddhism will help him overcome his 
addiction 
at first i said hes a junkie and junkies break down 
kelly says youve got to be desperate to come here because this 
is spiritual graduate school but keiths been a very very good 
student 
kelly says his own background as an lsd manufacturer and user 
makes him sympathetic to scofield kelly spent a year in federal 
prison in the 1980s for drug trafficking 
scofield could be a pioneer for the monastery which may take in 
more criminal drug users that would have been unthinkable two 
years ago says abbot eido roshi who founded the traditional 
japanese monastery in 1976 but the monastery is americanizing 
itself blending zen spiritual tradition with western worldliness 
drug rehabilitation experts say they had never heard of anyone 
trying to overcome addiction at a monastery but conceded that 
different addicts need different handling 
recovery is a journey for anyone who is addicted and people 
take different paths in their recovery says jane fedderly 
spokeswoman for the hazeldon rehabilitation center in center city 
minn 
the name of the game is recovery i wouldnt knock what hes 
doing 
scofields wellordered 16hour days are at least as taxing as 
the boot camp that awaited him in colorado he says and monastic 
life is far more strenuous than life in prison or a conventional 
drug program 
yet hes approaching his new life with zeal the day begins with 
group chanting before the monasterys carved wooden buddha after 
breakfast scofield works chopping wood painting repairing walls 
and ceilings 
four hours of meditation are spread throughout the day the 
longest period coming before the lights go out at 9 pm 
i really got lucky scofield says i didnt know what sort 
of place this would turn out to be i remember thinking what if 
its an old barn with 20 monks sitting in a circle chanting but 
then i thought it really doesnt matter as long as i change my 
life what i had before wasnt really much of a life 
</TEXT>
