<TEXT>
 
editors note carnegie hall once doomed to destruction 
celebrates its 100th birthday this season thank isaac stern the 
virtuoso violinist who has been president of the new york concert 
hall for the past 30 years rarely has a musician been so closely 
associated with a place 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
to isaac stern carnegie hall is a mystical 
place the mount olympus of american music for good reason 
the storied new york concert hall is where stern first vaulted 
into preeminence as a virtuoso violinist he returned the favor 
years later by saving carnegie hall from oblivion 
that was 30 years ago today as carnegie hall prepares to 
celebrate its 100th birthday stern reflects on its rich history as 
the cradle of american culture in the 20th century 
carnegie hall is entwined completely with the artistic 
emotional intellectual political growth of this country stern 
says its astonishing 
carnegie hall he adds was the place where you came to prove 
whether you belonged or not it has been the crown proving place 
for every single orchestra every conductor every pianist singer 
violinist cellist 
you walk in there you think of all the people whove been 
there its the center from which the entire development of 
american music came nothing happened in this country that didnt 
come through carnegie 
as a performer the violinist says carnegie hall makes a 
performance larger than life its an enormously powerful hall and 
it does give even average performers a glamour and power they 
wouldnt have in other halls 
with its coming 19901991 blockbuster season carnegie hall 
celebrates its 100th anniversary stern who celebrated his 70th 
birthday on july 21 says the important thing is to make sure 
itll be here for the next 100 years 
its something to hold on to some connection with mans 
involvement with education with the quality of civilization 
as for his own birthday he says i very honestly feel as if 
im reaching a good time of my middle age of course id be a 
little more sure of it if i knew very active people who were 140 
at a birthday celebration concert in san francisco actor 
gregory peck called stern an irresistible oneman cultural 
force 
surely no virtuoso instrumentalist has been as allied with a 
place as stern with carnegie hed played in new york twice at town 
hall receiving mild notices before performing at carnegie for the 
first time at age 22 in january 1943 reviews glowed 
that was the start of the career really he says from 
then on things really took off 
at home in manhattan wearing a shortsleeved shirt on a 
90degree day his glasses pushed atop his white hair stern agrees 
to pose for a picture holding his guarneri violin but he doesnt 
follow the photographers suggestion to hug the instrument with 
crossed arms 
unlike a woman you embrace a violin with great care not with 
great abandon he explains its more like a baby 
stern muses that 1943 in carnegie hall saw the start of the 
leonard bernstein era when the young assistant conductor of the 
new york philharmonic substituted on short notice for the ailing 
bruno walter 
it was the year the duke ellington band played black brown 
and beige starting ellingtons annual carnegie concerts 
premiering his extended compositions which often expressed racial 
pride 
stern recalls some of the historic concerts he attended at 
carnegie the great return of pianist vladimir horowitz after his 
absence the american debut of soviet violinist david oistrakh the 
last performances of violinist fritz kreisler 
it was clear kreisler was going to go into retirement at that 
time i remember particularly his last orchestral concert eugene 
ormandy wrapped him in musical cotton to take care of him during 
that whole performance it was moving touching very dear 
he remembers the time pianist arthur rubinstein gave 10 recitals 
in a row all of them for charity marian andersons farewell 
eleanor roosevelt coming to listen to a high school graduation 
performance 
in 1960 when lincoln center was being built and the new york 
philharmonic about to move from carnegie to the new philharmonic 
hall in the new music and theater complex the plan was to tear 
down the privately owned carnegie hall and build an office tower 
starting with meetings in friends apartments stern began raising 
money to mount a campaign to save the hall 
did he really think he could save it or was he making a symbolic 
gesture 
i never was a don quixote stern says i dont tilt at 
empty windmills i was completely convinced i was going to win if 
i had been less innocent i might have been afraid of how possible 
it was to lose 
i wasnt entirely innocent politically i knew i had to work 
politically 
after we knew we had won the fight and they were drafting the 
legislation that let the city buy carnegie hall i left as a member 
of a group to do a tour while we were in europe they voted me in 
as president of carnegie i havent quit yet 
being president of carnegie hall for 30 years has taken more 
time than most concert performers would be willing to sacrifice 
from their musical careers he hasnt minded stern says because 
the violin gave me the impetus and power to work for carnegie and 
that gave me a different set of tensions to make going back to the 
violin even more pleasurable 
stern has long worked to help fledgling musicians 
being of service has always seemed very natural to me i cant 
give you a reason i never thought of it as being of service 
people have been very nice to me ive been very fortunate a long 
time ago without being philosophical or creating a credo i just 
figured one has been fortunate so one has to give something back 
you dont just take so i do that 
im interested to tell young people why you play what happens 
between the notes where the music is made and to teach teachers 
how to get excited about how music is part of our lives 
a movie from mao to mozart in which stern shares music 
with youngsters in china won an oscar for best fulllength 
documentary in 1981 
stern and his wife vera have two sons who are conductors one 
married to a violinist the other engaged to an oboist their 
daughter and her husband who have three sons are both rabbis 
with synagogues 12 miles apart in new jersey 
vera and the children have helped me always stern says 
were a very close family we believe in loving and touching and 
thats a help 
</TEXT>
