<TEXT>
dont look for oneshot guest stars at the 
guthrie theater no television personalities and movie names 
brought in for marquee value or to give the box office a boost 
the guthrie is a company of actors 23 at last count who have 
made a nearly yearround commitment to the regional theater and its 
artistic director garland wright 
that was one of the reasons wright took the job in the summer of 
1986 it was a chance to build a permanent troupe of performers 
able to jump from shakespeare to shaw from wilde to wilder with 
ease 
the classical companys current challenging efforts are good 
examples of giving actors and audiences a stretch three 
shakespeare history plays richard ii henry iv and 
henry v are being performed in repertory all summer 
the emphasis in doing these plays was the acting company 
says charles newell who codirected the trio of shakespeare epics 
with wright the plays were chosen with the company in mind we 
didnt go to new york to get the leads and then cast the secondary 
parts locally which has been the case in the past 
casting from new york or los angeles or chicago is common 
practice among a lot of regional theaters most performers cant 
afford a steady diet of regional theater work 
when actors work mainly on a freelance basis they can do a 
soap opera for maybe 10 weeks at 3000 a week and then do a play 
at a regional theater for 300 a week says edward martenson the 
guthries executive director 
in other words the commercial side of their existence is 
subsidizing the art side he says its a question of at what 
level can actors afford to give up that commercial side in order to 
do what theyd like to do 
the guthrie which has a yearly operating budget of about 95 
million has tried to snare actors with two promises most 
performers cant resist good roles and more money 
the money is linked to an ambitious 25 million endowment plan 
which was started in the spring of 1987 and which martenson hopes 
to have closed out by the end of 1991 so far more than 16 
million has been raised much of it in large gifts from 
corporations and donations from several individuals 
our reasoning was that we could not hope to compete with the 
resources they have in hollywood or on broadway in terms of a 
weekly salary martenson says instead what were looking for 
is the ability of an actor or actress to settle here and make a 
fulltime commitment 
one actress who has done just that is brenda wehle who plays 
small roles in henry iv and henry v and will have a major 
part in the skin of our teeth and the title role in medea 
when they open later in the season 
wehle first came to minneapolis five years ago for five months 
with a production of eric overmyers on the verge directed by 
wright she was living in philadelphia at the time and going where 
she had to places such as hartford conn and seattle for 
acting jobs 
garland called seven months later when i was back in 
philadelphia and he said can you be here in two weeks for longer 
than five months she recalls i moved out bought a house 
with a white picket fence bought a car all the dreams you have 
put my two children in school and began as a member of the new 
company four seasons ago 
charles janasz who plays richard ii ned poins in henry iv 
and the dauphin in henry v arrived at the guthrie last year 
he had been in a similar acting company at arena stage in 
washington and loved it 
he also had tried new york and found he had to go outoftown to 
get work 
unless youre dead set on making a career move into film and 
television i see no reason for not moving here unless you like 
instability he says im happy when im working and im not 
happy when im not working so when i was living in new york the 
only time i was happy was when i was away from home 
other actors in the company came from as far away as across 
town local actors wright has pulled into his troupe stephen 
yoakam who plays bolingbroke in richard ii and later the title 
character in henry iv went to college in minneapolis and for 
the most part stayed 
in 1986 the guthrie had only six actors under contract for a 
year but the most any actor could earn then in a full season at 
the guthrie was 24000 martenson says 
on that you cant buy a house settle down and have a 
family he says our objective was to get to an average of 950 
a week which would work out for a 45week season to a little 
more than 42000 a year that would put our highest salary at 
something like 50000 for a fulltime actor on that we feel 
people can afford to make a fulltime commitment to us 
those levels havent been reached yet 
weve still got two steps to go phased in over a period of 
six years martenson says but the progress that weve made so 
far and the commitments that weve gotten from people make it clear 
that the money increase has been a very significant factor 
the variety and quality of the roles offered these actors have 
been just as important in compelling them to stay at the guthrie 
theres been a steady upward climb in terms of the size of the 
roles weve been undertaking and the responsibility that has been 
given to us as members of an ensemble yoakam says 
</TEXT>
