<TEXT>
 
lineage blue note benny green 
 
jazz pianist benny green is just 27 but he demonstrates a 
veterans appreciation and feel for classic jazz and bebop in his 
first solo title album lineage green plays strong and spunky 
on every selection chosen for this compact disc from bobby 
timmons dat dere to monks ask me now 
he also stretches his talents from fusion to show tunes he has 
included a wonderfully syrupy version of lerner and lowes if 
ever i would leave you and adds a light fusion number of his own 
called trust although his other three compositions steer 
closer to classic jazz 
green who has played with frank morgan betty carter and 
freddie hubbard is backed solidly by bassist ray drummond and 
victor lewis on drums but the album is clearly greens chance to 
shine the selection and order of numbers flow smoothly making for 
an impresive first album by an ascending new talent 
by thomas ginsberg associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
carmen suite larlesienne suite no 1 symphony no 1 by 
georges bizet telarc cincinnati symphony orchestra jesus 
lopezcobos conductor 
 
oh well one might say here are a couple more war horses by a 
middlerank orchestra and ambitious conductor one might also be 
very much mistaken because this is a stunning recording 
lopezcobos draws out freshsounding vivid and supple 
performances with beautifully shaped lines and tight rhythmic 
control the orchestra glows and the winds play superbly a worthy 
compact disc 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
masses no 2 and 6 by franz schubert telarc atlanta 
symphony orchestra amp chorus conducted by robert shaw telarc 
 
shaw conducts detailed nicely phrased and wellbalanced if a 
little bland performances of a good sampling of schuberts sacred 
music on this compact disc generously timed at 7745 schubert 
wrote no 2 at the age of 17 and it is quite a bit simpler than 
no 6 which was composed in the final year of his pathetically 
short life 
the contrast is interesting in fact the straightforward 
innocence of the earlier work makes it more appealing the soloists 
are generally admirable particularly soprano dawn upshaw in no 2 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
blazing away island records marianne faithfull 
 
this mostly live offering by one of rocks legendary survivors 
carries a warning label about its lyrics but ought to caution 
listeners to beware its emotional punch 
twelve of the 13 songs were recorded during two 1989 concerts in 
a brooklyn ny cathedral in effect the collection is a musical 
autobiography of faithfull who burst onto the pop scene as a 
teenager in the 1960s faded away in a heroin haze in the 1970s 
and returned in the 80s with the critically acclaimed but 
hardtoenjoy album broken english 
i bought broken english in 1981 and gave it away not long 
after unable to bear the ragged voice that once had sung so 
sweetly on as tears go by 
faithfull sings as tears go by on blazing away and it is 
beautiful her voice is still harsh but the ache in it feels real 
and the spare arrangement featuring an accordion solo by garth 
hudson gently colors the melancholy mood 
the album also contains powerfully moving readings of john 
lennons working class hero and the rolling stones sister 
morphine a song for which faithfull wrote the lyrics during her 
longago union with mick jagger 
another highlight is the ballad of lucy jordan a song of 
middleage madness by shel silverstein that faithfull has made one 
of her signature tunes 
her band on the live numbers boasts in addition to hudson new 
orleans piano king dr john and guitarist marc ribot who also has 
played on recent tom waits and elvis costello recordings 
but despite the fine sound and faithfulls evocative vocals 
shes still a difficult act to enjoy many of her best songs are 
downers and the timbre of her voice reveals as much about pain and 
hard times as the lyrics 
there are rewards here but only for listeners willing to open 
their minds and drop their preconceptions 
by david dishneau associated press writer 
</TEXT>
