<TEXT>
the restoration of an abandoned 
shopping mall to its turnofthecentury elegance has sparked hopes 
that other aging architectural gems may be preserved rather than 
knocked down or allowed to crumble 
galerias pacifico covers an entire city block along the florida 
street pedestrian walkway that cuts through the heart of buenos 
aires commercial district 
modeled on vittorio emanuele ii gallery in milan it was a 
showpiece from its marble halls to glass roof when it opened 100 
years ago 
i remember going there when i was a girl it was marvelous 
wonderful said nene martinez castro director of casa foa a 
group that redecorates interesting buildings and sells admission 
tickets to raise money for charity 
as an adult i thought it was a glory and then a shame when 
it went to waste she said 
galerias pacifico received a facelift of sorts in the 1940s 
huge frescoes by some of argentinas most gifted painters 
spilimbergo urruchua berni were added as decoration around a 
central dome but the glass roof was covered by an arch of 
reinforced concrete 
the building eventually was taken over by the state which tried 
beginning a decade ago to sell it services deteriorated and 
discouraged tenants left one by one 
in recent years galerias pacifico whose wellkept neighbors 
include the plaza hotel harrods department store and the 
glittering naval officers club became an eyesore of broken 
windows sagging marquees and boardedup entrances 
it was home no longer to boutiques for leather fur toys and 
books but to pigeons rats and decrepit men and women with no 
other place to call their own 
this capital city of 10 million has a lot of buildings that date 
back to when beef and grain exports made argentina one of the 
richest countries in the world and money was lavished on homes 
offices plazas and boulevards 
retiro train station inaugurated in 1915 was inspired by 
londons victoria station the facade of la prensa once the 
biggest newspaper in latin america recalls the paris opera 
many buildings boast art deco touches such as columns molded in 
the shape of giants who appear to sustain the structures on 
shoulders and backs of bulging muscle 
others have towering lobbies of italian marble stairways of 
german oak elevators with wrought iron grillwork and wooden 
benches interior patios with statues and fountains windows big 
enough to stand in balconies turrets gables cupolas 
the central hall of the national library is lined by bookcases 
of polished wood that stretch up several stories to a dome that 
allows in enough light to read by 
such buildings add to a citys culture a citys affluence 
its spirit said architect elizabeth kries im not against new 
things but there are some buildings that have values you should 
not lose 
while pleasing to the eye such buildings often are drafty 
awkward to organize and deficient in plumbing heating air 
conditioning and access for the handicapped 
the library train station and la prensa are in advanced states 
of deterioration when owners of other buildings were faced with 
finally doing something many concluded in the 1960s and 70s that 
it was easier to tear down than remodel 
everyone believed modern was better kries said the 
united states put a man on the moon people saw old buildings 
as old things old ideas they didnt appreciate them 
such thinking has begun to change 
casa foa last year redesigned an abandoned textile factory 
into spacious loft apartments that helped start a trend plans are 
afoot to do the same with warehouses along buenos aires decaying 
waterfront 
another group converted a derelict central market into an 
openair theater whose first production was federico garcia lorcas 
bodas de sangre blood wedding 
when it bought the alzaga unzue palace in downtown buenos aires 
several years ago the hyatt corporation reportedly intended to 
demolish the 76yearold mansion now company officials plan to 
use it as a lobby for what will be a fivestar hotel 
jose maria pena director of the city museum and a conservator 
who helped draft zoning laws to protect old buildings said its 
too soon to say if all that amounts to a trend 
in general builders still think its easier to take down a 
building and put up something new he said 
but pena added there are a lot of examples of restorations 
and there is a trend of people wanting to live in old buildings 
that have more space and privacy 
and buildings that look a little more distinguished 
a majority of buildings built in the 1960s and 70s have 
prematurely aged said pena they look more worn out than 
buildings built at the turn of the century that wear their age with 
dignity 
