forget the fire a character says in 
john edgar widemans new novel play with fire you know what 
happens youll get burnt like the rest of us 
wideman not known for sticking to safe topics cant forget the 
1985 move confrontation that killed 11 people and destroyed a 
philadelphia neighborhood 
i dont think its something that should be put to rest he 
said in a telephone interview from his home in amherst mass i 
think it should be kept alive and used creatively no more than 
the holocaust should be put to rest 
the acclaimed author of brothers and keepers and sent for 
you yesterday makes his case in philadelphia fire scheduled 
for september release by henry holt 
the move confrontation becomes a complex metaphor for black 
america urban decay love power and justice in the 
unconventional earthy narrative wideman alludes to the slave 
trade shakespeares caliban the birth of the blues and the 
drumbeat call of a basketball game in a west philadelphia park 
the books central character searches for a survivor of the 
fire but finds a reflection of himself instead the narrators son 
is in prison as is widemans though the author said the account 
is not strictly autobiographical 
all these characters merge he said they flow in and 
out 
wideman and his wife judy lived during the late 1960s on osage 
avenue two miles from where the move radicals later spent a year 
harassing their middleclass black neighbors and broadcasting 
obscenities and calls for revolution from a public address system 
day and night 
the narrator of philadelphia fire registers shock when he 
learns police bombed the radicals fortified row house may 13 
1985 and let a neighborhood burn in a bungled eviction attempt 
the narrator thinks hes looking at a war zone or a third 
world shantytown where theres no water no machines to extinguish 
a fire when the scene erupts on television 
wideman felt similar shock when he learned of the conflagration 
he said in the interview he had played basketball with people in 
the neighborhood and wondered how the crisis evolved 
something in a way had been done to me he said something 
had been done to my past as i learned more about the move people 
i recalled also that if i didnt know those particular people i 
knew people like them people who were around me people who had 
been dropouts who had been radicals in the 60s people who had 
given up on the system in the 60s black and white 
at the same time he said he shared the feelings of people who 
had been subjected to abuse by move members i have great 
sympathy and understanding of them because thats more or less the 
kind of world i come from he said theyre my people 
