the unbelieveable truth 
the unbelieveable truth made for a whopping 200000 is a 
relative bargain in this summer of milliondollar adventures its 
a debut film irreverent and unpredictable but less selfassured 
when it tries to get serious 
the movie was written and directed by hal hartley who graduated 
from the film school of the state university of new york at 
purchase in 1984 and is a pretty irreverent sort himself he 
raised some of the money by telling the bank he was buying a word 
processor the actors are all virtually new to film and shooting 
on location at lindenhurst long island took just 11 days 
josh hutton robert burke is released from prison after serving 
time were told for raping and killing a girl and then killing 
her father dressed in black the softspoken josh is continously 
mistaken for a priest and must admit instead that hes merely a 
mechanic and a prison mechanic at that 
when josh isnt working on cars hes discussing life with mike 
a fellow mechanic heavy metal guitarist and selfstyled 
philosopher you start cleaning yourself a lot better mike 
says about what happens to a man when he has a girlfriend 
suddenly youre buying underwear up the whazoo 
audry hugo adrienne shelly is a doeeyed high school senior 
who spends much of her free time thinking about nuclear war her 
parents want her to go to college but the way audry sees it 
well all be lucky to be alive in september 
josh and audry meet after audrys father gives him a job at his 
local garage josh may be a mass murderer but hes the only who 
knows how to fix a foreign car audry has dumped her nerdy 
boyfriend after he greets her one morning in a jacket and tie and 
she is immediately attracted to josh 
there are of course other complications audrys father 
christopher cooke objects to the relationship offering josh a 
raise in return for leaving her alone and audry unable to get 
josh to sleep with her leaves lindenhurst to pursue a modeling 
career 
hartley shows a nice touch for deadpan humor and as black 
comedy the film works cooke is especially funny ranting and 
fuming like a stressedout ward cleaver ready with a parental 
cliche for all occasions the director also takes full advantage of 
the low budget even switching from one scene to the next by 
showing a flash card that reads meanwhile 
but audrys reflections on nuclear war wear thin and hartleys 
message about emotional capitalism the way relationships are 
conducted like business seems forced 
the film is simply too detached to make anyone really worry 
about the characters achieving emotional truth after all theyll 
be lucky to be alive in september 
the unbelievable truth was produced by hartley and bruce 
weiss with jerome brownstein as executive producer the film is 
rated r for language and adult situations 
by hillel italie associated press writer 
