the french computer firm groupe bull sa announced 
monday plans to cut 3000 jobs during 1990 and said losses for the 
first six months this year were three times larger than in the same 
period in 1989 
the troubled computer maker said in a statement it would lay off 
3000 workers to streamline manufacturing and research operations 
in north america ireland and france 
the stateowned company predicted earlier this year that only 
1200 layoffs would be necessary 
bull said losses from january through june 1990 totaled 188 
billion francs or 355 million up from a loss of 537 million 
francs in the first half of 1989 
the latest loss stemmed in part from bulls acquisition of the 
dataprocessing units of zenith electronic corp last year the 
company said 
consolidated revenue rose to 159 billion francs or 28 
billion in the first half from 140 billion francs in the same 
period in 1989 
bulls loss comes amid a general downturn among 
mainframecomputer makers standardization has cut demand for 
costly proprietary systems and has sliced profit margins for 
companies that havent adapted 
the french concern said earlier this year that it planned to cut 
1200 jobs from its work force to cope with the slowdown and 
changes in the industry 
bull said sales picked up in june after declining for five 
straight months and noted it normally earns about 60 percent of its 
revenue in the second half of the year 
the company posted a loss of 267 million francs in 1989 
following a profit of 303 million francs the previous year 
