<TEXT>
the professor was very hungry for a hamburger 
but then as sometimes happens to professors he reached into his 
pocket and found no money he would have to do without 
he didnt think it was fair just a few minutes before he had 
paid for a doctors visit with a credit card receiving in return a 
bill marked paid in full his health insurance company would 
reimburse him 
he mused if i had hamburger insurance i would not have this 
problem i could have had my hamburger already eaten it without a 
dime in my pocket he thought the idea had promise everyone 
eats hamburgers he thought 
and so with tongue in the cheek where he had hoped to have a 
hamburger he devised a plan to allow all americans in need of a 
patty to have one free and open access to hamburgers a rather 
basic right he mused 
the professor an economist named william dunkelberg who also 
is dean of the school of business and management at temple 
university in philadelphia decided to explore the idea it might 
relieve his craving 
the plan is simple he explained it would work like all 
the other insurance programs we just add up total burger 
expenditures divide by the number of people and arrive at an 
average premium 
any individual who paid this premium perhaps 40 a year would 
receive a walletsize hamburger insurance card the money would go 
into a hamburger insurance trust which would repay the burger 
joint 
as he drove back to the office the notion grew he saw millions 
of people signing up and multimillions of dollars pouring into the 
hamburger trust it would be a whopping success 
then the bills arrived from the hamburger providers and it was 
very clear that the bills exceeded the insurance premiums collected 
how could this be asked trust officials we charged each 
person the average amount spent on hamburgers in the united states 
plus 5 for overhead expenses such as maintaining our respectable 
but by no means posh offices 
congress established the hamburger commission to investigate and 
report it found people who didnt eat hamburgers didnt sign up 
for the program thus revenues were less than projected 
the commission recommended that congress make hamburger 
insurance mandatory so that no one could escape responsibility for 
funding such important coverage some commission members thought 
this was not enough 
why because those who originally signed up for the program 
bought even more hamburgers than they had before they had the 
insurance these heavy eaters not only were buying more hamburgers 
but more expensive ones as well 
a number of beneficiaries were using the insurance card to buy 
burgers for their pets and drivethrough customers were ordering 
an extra burger for the road in case they got hungry they could 
always throw it away 
producers innovated too triple deckers became the norm and 
burgers made of ground filet were especially popular as business 
lunches and among the tennis and garden club set at higher prices 
of course and delivery extra 
the hamburger trust was endangered without insurance many 
people would be unable to afford hamburgers business people warned 
that a failure of the trust would destroy jobs and force small 
companies out of business 
it was decided that a tax subsidy was needed to save the 
program no one declared an heroic cattlestate senator 
should escape responsibility for maintaining this american 
institution 
premiums were raised and made mandatory taxes were raised too 
reducing consumer disposable income and making people more reliant 
on the hamburger program for basic food 
the impact was immediate more expensive hamburgers were 
introduced more companies entered the business and they offered 
more services fully covered by premiums fewer people ate at 
home they couldnt afford to 
the federal budget deficit grew and it was urgently suggested 
by some throwbacks to another time that the program be curtailed to 
save the economy not a chance it was an election year 
at that point the professor dropped the idea as a very dangerous 
one the idea he confessed had lost its appeal quite a contrast 
to his original pride in thinking it up 
he had lost his taste for a hamburger forget it he said 
swallowing his pride instead 
</TEXT>
