<TEXT>
confidence in the nations economy among 
consumers was about the same in july as in june according to a 
monthly private study released tuesday 
consumers were slightly more positive about present conditions 
than in june but a little less positive about their expectations 
for the months ahead the conference board reported 
the conclusions were based on a monthly survey of 5000 
households nationwide conducted by the board of family opinion inc 
in toledo ohio 
consumer confidence has been losing ground since the beginning 
of the year but the experience has been markedly different in 
various regions of the country said fabian linden executive 
director of the boards consumer research center 
linden said confidence was sharply lower in new england in the 
second quarter of 1990 compared with the same period a year earlier 
expectations in the middle atlantic states also were lower 
while consumer confidence was up in the west central and mountain 
regions confidence was lower in the pacific states than a year ago 
but above the level in the rest of the nation 
of those surveyed 232 percent said business conditions were 
good in july up from 226 percent the previous month and 256 
percent said jobs were plentiful up from 234 percent in june 
but more respondents 117 percent in july compared with 104 
percent in june said they expected business conditions to worsen 
in the next six months also 179 percent said they expected there 
would be fewer jobs available in the next six months up from 165 
percent in june 
buying plans were mixed eight percent said they planned to buy 
a car and 43 percent a home in the next six months both up from 
june but overall plans to purchase major appliances declined to 
268 percent from 288 percent in june 
the conference board is a nonprofit business research 
organization 
