william h donaldson a founder of the 
securities firm donaldson lufkin amp jenrette inc is the leading 
candidate to become chairman of the new york stock exchange 
sources said monday 
the current chairman john j phelan jr is retiring at the end 
of 1990 after six years heading the nations largest stock exchange 
a final decision by the nyses board is expected to be made 
within two weeks donaldson may not emerge as the final selection 
but is considered the leading candidate according to people 
familiar with the selection process who asked not to be named 
an eightmember search committee has been meeting since phelan 
announced his retirement in february 
donaldson 59 now heads donaldson enterprises inc a merchant 
banking and money management firm in new york he did not return 
telephone calls monday seeking comment 
new york stock exchange spokesman richard torrenzano would 
neither confirm nor deny whether donaldson would be recommended to 
succeed phelan to the full exchange board 
torrenzano said the search panel has been diligently and 
thoughtfully talking to people throughout the securities industry 
as well as key corporate leaders for their input 
donaldson was one of three founders of the securities firm that 
bears his name he left donaldson lufkin in 1973 to become an 
undersecretary of state to henry kissinger he later founded and 
was the first dean of yale universitys school of organization and 
management 
phelan has been widely praised for leading the exchange 
successfully through the 1987 stock market crash that devastated 
investor confidence among the issues to be faced by a new leader 
are the nyses slowly shrinking market share increased competition 
from other exchanges the introduction of new technology 
