<TEXT>
fujistu ltd the second largest mainframe 
computer maker in the world announced monday it has agreed to buy 
britains top computer manufacturer international computers ltd 
for 12 billion 
the buyout will make fujitsu the second largest computer group 
in the world after usbased international business machines 
corp officials with the japanese company said at a news 
conference 
analysts have said the purchase would give fujitsu a major sales 
and manufacturing foothold in europe ahead of the creation of the 
single european market in 1992 
it also makes the japanese giant a player in the european 
mainframe market for the first time ibm now dominates that market 
michio naruto fujitsus managing director and vice general 
manager of international operations in tokyo said the acquisition 
illustrates the emergence of the 168 billion japanese company as 
a truly global computer maker 
he acknowledged that the purchase might renew fears of japanese 
buyouts in some parts of europe 
but he sought to allay concerns by saying that icl would 
continue to be europeanrun icl which currently does 60 percent 
of its business in britain already has said its intention was to 
expand to europe fujitsu intends to support this intention 
naruto said 
for icls part the deal provides the mainframe manufacturer 
with the funds and technology for research and development and for 
its planned thrust in europe 
icls ability to grow will be significantly enhanced as a 
member of the fujitsu family said arthur walsh chairman and 
chief executive officer of stc plc the parent company of icl at a 
london news conference 
fujitsu chairman takuma yamamoto said his company intends to 
seek a separate listing for icl on londons international stock 
exchange as soon as practicable 
under the agreement fujitsu will pay icls parent company stc 
plc 700 million pounds or about 12 billion for an 80 percent 
stake in the british computer firm icl itself will pay stc an 
additional 428 million pounds or about 734 million 
there had been rumors for about a year about a possible equity 
tie between icl and fujitsu which already have technology links 
according to london analysts 
icl uses fujitsus computer chips and disks under a 
nineyearold agreement 
analysts consider icl to be europes most profitable mainframe 
computer maker yet in the first six months of the year the 
company suffered a 74 percent decline in operating profit to 107 
million on sales of 14 billion 
analysts said fujitsu has the financial strength to help icl 
withstand what is expected to be an increasingly competitive 
european market 
we have come to respect icl in the course of our technological 
collaboration in the last nine years and this agreement builds on 
that relationship said yamamoto 
he said icls chairman and managing director peter bonfield 
would continue in that position 
fujitsus major activity in europe is selling semiconductor 
computer chips although it makes office computers in spain and 
semiconductors in ireland 
