developing countries of southeast asia deplored 
the lack of progress in international trade negotiations and said 
monday that they feared being left out in the economic cold 
in a strongly worded statement criticising developed nations 
indonesia malaysia the philippines singapore and thailand 
saidwe are concerned that deals will be struck among the 
principals in the fall and developing countries will be left out in 
the cold 
there seems to be no point in going further if this is going 
to be the scenario we call on developed countries to show 
leadership in the market access negotiations said the statement 
by the four countries which together with brunei make up the 
association of southeast asian nations known as asean 
stating that the group places special emphasis on market access 
it added asean views progress in this area as the gauge by which 
to measure the seriousness of developed countries in taking 
developing country concerns into account 
the global negotiations are called the uruguay round of trade 
negotiations aimed at better market access and freer trade the 
round is scheduled to conclude in december 
the possibility that the round will end as a failure does 
not seem unthinkable the statement said giving details of how 
the developed nations were attaching conditions for tax concessions 
and quotas for tropical products textiles agricultural and farm 
products and other goods 
the asean nations are attending the ninemonthold asia pacific 
economic cooperation apec meeting here monday and tuesday where 
they differed with the developed nations in discussions on the 
trade talks 
the other members of the 12nation apec are the united states 
japan canada australia new zealand and south korea 
two separate statements were issued on their discussions a mild 
one by apec and a strongly worded one by asean 
asked why there were differences singapores trade minister lee 
hsien loong told a news conference there were differences on 
naunces of views but he said they were united in wanting 
faster progress 
but a senior asean official who spoke on condition he would not 
be identified by name saidof course there are deep differences 
at the rate we are going they will give us nothing or very little 
that is why our views were expressed so strongly 
the apec statement said the trade talks had not made enough 
progress and it was the single most important issue on the 
international agenda 
japanese foreign minister taro nakayama asked apec to admit 
china taiwan and hong kong which want to be members but 
conference officials said they doubted they would be admitted here 
although membership was possible later 
