<DOCNO> AP900730-0227 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
blinder robinson amp co inc once the nations 
largest pennystock brokerage firm on monday asked us bankruptcy 
court for protection from creditors while it reorganizes 
in a brief news release monday night announcing the filing under 
chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws the firm said it plans to 
transfer its customer accounts and brokerage operations to another 
brokerdealer 
earlier this month the securities and exchange commission 
charged the troubled colorado brokerage of overcharging investors 
by more than 20 million in 21 months 
according to a lawsuit filed in us district court blinder 
robinson marked up prices as high as 140 percent on penny stocks 
when selling them to investors 
the sec claimed the activity took place from june 1985 through 
february 1987 
last april the sec suspended blinder robinson from trading in 
penny stocks for 45 days and from underwriting such offerings for 
two years the sec also barred the firms founder and chairman 
meyer blinder from associating with any registered brokerdealer 
for at least two years 
blinder 69 of denver and four associates were indicted in 
february on racketeering and securities fraud charges by a federal 
grand jury in las vegas the indictment followed a 1988 internal 
revenue service raid on blinder robinsons denver office 
penny stocks are low cost high risk securities usually trading 
for less than 3 per share they are not listed on stock exchanges 
and typically are used to raise capital for new or small companies 
</TEXT>
